An Act protecting victims of childhood sexual abuse and holding perpetrators accountable.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Section 4C of chapter 260 of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022
2 Official Edition, is hereby amended by striking out the first paragraph and inserting in place
3 thereof the following paragraph:
4 Notwithstanding any general or special law to the contrary, a civil action alleging a
5 defendant sexually abused a minor may be commenced at any time after the acts alleged to have
6 caused an injury or condition occurred.
7 SECTION 2. Said chapter 260 is hereby amended by striking out section 4C½ and
8 inserting in place thereof the following section:
9 Section 4C½. Notwithstanding any general or special law to the contrary, and
10 notwithstanding the requirements of the Massachusetts Tort Claims Act, Mass. Gen. Law. C. 258
11 §4, any civil action alleging that a defendant negligently supervised a person who sexually
12 abused a minor or that a defendant’s acts or omissions caused or contributed to the sexual abuse
1 of 4

13 of a minor by another person may be commenced at any time after the acts or omissions alleged
14 to have caused an injury or condition occurred. For the purposes of this section, “sexual abuse”
15 shall have the same meaning as in section 4C.
16 SECTION 3. Revival of Time Barred Claims
17 Notwithstanding any general or special law to the contrary, and notwithstanding the
18 requirements of the Massachusetts Tort Claims Act, Mass. Gen. Law. C. 258 §4, all causes of
19 action for injuries or conditions related to the sexual abuse of a minor, as defined in section 4C,
20 that would have been barred by virtue of the expiration of a civil statute of limitations, notice of
21 claim or presentation deadline, or any other time limit that expired, or for which a final
22 judgement was rendered based on the expiration of any time limitation prior to the effective date
23 of this section is hereby revived and may be commenced within two years from the effective date
24 of this Act. This section applies to both individual and institutional defendants, whether public,
25 private, or charitable and is intended to govern all civil causes of action related to child sexual
26 abuse, including but not limited to claims involving ordinary negligence, vicarious liability,
27 and/or respondeat superior. This section is intended to be retroactive to the fullest extent of the
28 law, including revival of previously expired causes of actions.
29 SECTION 4. Section 5B of said chapter 260 is hereby amended by inserting the
30 following after the word “accrues”:
31 ; provided, however, that an action commenced under 20 U.S.C. §§1681-1688 related to
32 child sexual abuse, as defined in section 4C, shall be governed by the provisions of section 4C½.
33 SECTION 5. Section 85K of chapter 231 of the General Laws is hereby amended by
34 inserting, in line 12, after the word “costs” the following language:
